  {
    "name": "submit_planner_outcome",
    "description": "Terminate your planner run by submitting the generator/reducer DAG for this attempt.\n\n## Inputs\n- `tasks`: generator tasks, each with `id`, `agent_name`, and `needs`.\n- `task_specs`: mapping from each generator task id to its executable task text.\n- `reducers`: reducer tasks, each with `id`, one or more generator `needs`, and `prompt`.\n- `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration`: optional concrete goal items from the\n  current iteration goal that this plan intentionally leaves for the next\n  iteration. Omit or null means this plan covers all current-iteration goal\n  items and leaves no remaining items.\n\n## Behavior\n- With no deferred goal, the plan closes the current iteration once reducers pass.\n- With a nonblank deferred goal, the plan completes this bounded iteration and\n  carries those remaining current-iteration goal items into the next iteration.\n- The attempt PASSES iff every plan task reaches DONE.\n\n## Plan DAG Contract\n\nA plan is a DAG of generator + reducer tasks. Generators do the work; reducers\nwork on assigned reducer tasks using their direct `needs` as context, then\nreport outcome summaries. Use the smallest graph that matches the context flow.\n\nRules:\n- Root generators may have no `needs`.\n- Non-root generator `needs` may reference one or more generator ids.\n- Reducer `needs` must reference one or more generator ids.\n- No task may need a reducer; reducers are terminal sinks.\n- Every generator must be needed by another generator or by a reducer.\n\nContext rule:\n- `needs` are direct context inputs, not scheduling shortcuts.\n- A task receives only the outcomes of ids listed in its own `needs`;\n  transitive ancestors are not included.\n- If `gen_b` needs `gen_a` and `gen_c` needs `gen_b`, then `gen_c` receives\n  `gen_b` only.\n- If `gen_c` also needs `gen_a`'s context, set\n  `gen_c.needs = [\"gen_a\", \"gen_b\"]`.\n\nValid examples:\n\nOverview graph:\n   gen_a ----\\\n              +---> gen_c ----\\\n   gen_b ----/                +---> gen_e ----\\\n             \\                /               +---> red_f\n              +---> gen_d ----+--------------/\n   gen_c -----------------------------------> red_g\n\n1. One full serial lane:\n   gen_a -> gen_b -> gen_c -> red_d\n\n2. Multiple serial lanes:\n   gen_a -> gen_b -> red_e\n   gen_c -> gen_d -> red_f\n\n3. Simple fan-in reducer:\n   gen_a ----\\\n   gen_b -----+---> red_d\n   gen_c ----/\n\n4. Diamond fork-join:\n              +---> gen_b ----\\\n   gen_a ----+                +---> gen_d ----> red_e\n              +---> gen_c ----/\n\n5. Tree:\n   gen_a\n   +---> gen_b ----\\\n   |               +---> red_f\n   +---> gen_c ----/\n        +---> gen_d ----> red_g\n        +---> gen_e ----> red_h\n\n6. Fully-connected layers:\n   gen_a ----+---> gen_c ----+---> red_e\n             |              |\n   gen_b ----+---> gen_d ----+---> red_f\n\n7. Multi-phase mesh:\n   gen_a ----> gen_c ----\\\n                         +---> gen_e ----\\\n   gen_b ----> gen_d ----/                +---> gen_h ----\\\n                         +---> gen_f ----/                +---> red_i\n   gen_c -----------------------------------------------> red_j\n\n## Close vs Defer Decision\n\nCall `submit_planner_outcome` without `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration` when:\n- This iteration's generator work and reducer outcomes are enough to finish the\n  current iteration goal.\n- The plan covers all current-iteration goal items and leaves no remaining\n  items.\n\nCall `submit_planner_outcome` with nonblank `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration` when:\n- You have a concrete plan for a bounded subset of the current iteration goal,\n  and the listed remaining current-iteration goal items should move to the next\n  iteration after this iteration's reducer outcomes exist.\n- The current plan is concrete; what would be speculative is planning the full\n  goal beyond this iteration before those reducer outcomes exist.\n- Once current reducers complete successfully, their outcomes become\n  prior-iteration context for the next planner, alongside\n  `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration`.\n- The deferred goal is concrete remaining current-iteration goal items, not a\n  generic backlog dump or unrelated future idea.\n\nExamples:\n- Lane shape does not decide close vs defer. A sequence like\n  `gen_a -> gen_b -> gen_c -> ...` can close or defer depending on whether\n  another planner pass is needed.\n- Omit `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration` when the collection of reducer\n  outcomes is sufficient for the current iteration goal and leaves no remaining\n  items.\n- Set `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration` when the reducers produce iteration\n  outcomes that should become context for the next planner, and\n  `deferred_goal_for_next_iteration` lists the remaining current-iteration goal\n  items.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "definitions": {
        "PlanTaskInput": {
          "properties": {
            "agent_name": {
              "type": "string"
            },
            "id": {
              "type": "string"
            },
            "needs": {
              "default": [],
              "items": {
                "type": "string"
              },
              "type": "array"
            }
          },
          "required": [
            "agent_name",
            "id"
          ],
          "type": "object"
        },
        "ReducerInput": {
          "properties": {
            "id": {
              "type": "string"
            },
            "needs": {
              "default": [],
              "items": {
                "type": "string"
              },
              "type": "array"
            },
            "prompt": {
              "type": "string"
            }
          },
          "required": [
            "id",
            "prompt"
          ],
          "type": "object"
        }
      },
      "properties": {
        "deferred_goal_for_next_iteration": {
          "default": null,
          "type": [
            "string",
            "null"
          ]
        },
        "reducers": {
          "items": {
            "$ref": "#/definitions/ReducerInput"
          },
          "type": "array"
        },
        "task_specs": {
          "additionalProperties": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "type": "object"
        },
        "tasks": {
          "items": {
            "$ref": "#/definitions/PlanTaskInput"
          },
          "type": "array"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "reducers",
        "task_specs",
        "tasks"
      ],
      "title": "SubmitPlannerOutcomeInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "submit_root_outcome",
    "description": "Terminate the root request with SUCCESS or FAILED.\n\n- `status`: \"success\" when the user request is complete and verified; \"failed\" when it cannot be completed.\n- `outcome`: the user-facing request result (for success) or the concrete blocker (for failure). The outcome is returned to the user.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "definitions": {
        "SubmissionStatus": {
          "description": "`Literal[\"success\", \"failed\"]`.",
          "enum": [
            "success",
            "failed"
          ],
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "properties": {
        "outcome": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "status": {
          "$ref": "#/definitions/SubmissionStatus"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "outcome",
        "status"
      ],
      "title": "SubmitRootOutcomeInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "submit_generator_outcome",
    "description": "Terminate your generator run with SUCCESS or FAILED for the current generator task.\n\n## Inputs\n- `status`: `\"success\"` when the assigned task is complete, or `\"failed\"`\n  when it cannot be completed in this attempt.\n- `outcome`: 1-3 sentence factual report. For success, include what changed,\n  verification evidence, and artifact references. For failure, include the\n  concrete blocker and evidence.\n\n## Do Not Use This Tool When\n- A delegated workflow you started is still outstanding; use\n  `delegate_workflow` only for new delegated work, then inspect or\n  cancel outstanding workflow handles before submitting your final outcome.\n\n## Behavior\n- Records reducer-visible generator success or failure on the current task.\n- The orchestrator advances the DAG after the submission is accepted.\n\n## Success vs Failure Decision\n\nGenerator task:\n- Treat `<dependencies>` outcomes as context inputs for your `<assigned_task>`.\n- Work on the assigned generator task, use `delegate_workflow` only\n  when a subtask needs delegated decomposition, then choose exactly one terminal\n  tool after all delegated work is resolved.\n\nCall `submit_generator_outcome` with `status=\"success\"` when:\n- You completed the assigned task and the deliverable is in place.\n- Required verification passed, or the task did not require verification.\n- Your `outcome` identifies what downstream tasks or reducers should read,\n  including verification and artifact references.\n\nCall `submit_generator_outcome` with `status=\"failed\"` when:\n- You attempted the assigned task but cannot complete it in this attempt.\n- The blocker is concrete enough for retry or replanning.\n- Delegated workflow results still leave the assigned task incomplete.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "definitions": {
        "SubmissionStatus": {
          "description": "`Literal[\"success\", \"failed\"]`.",
          "enum": [
            "success",
            "failed"
          ],
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "properties": {
        "outcome": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "status": {
          "$ref": "#/definitions/SubmissionStatus"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "outcome",
        "status"
      ],
      "title": "OutcomeInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "submit_reducer_outcome",
    "description": "Terminate your reducer run with SUCCESS or FAILED for the current reducer task.\n\n## Inputs\n- `status`: `\"success\"` when the assigned reducer work is complete, or\n  `\"failed\"` when it cannot be completed from the current context.\n- `outcome`: 1-3 sentence summary of the completed reducer result or the\n  concrete blocker/missing context.\n\n## Behavior\n- Records reducer success or failure on this task.\n- A successful reducer can close the attempt once every plan task is done.\n- A failed reducer causes the attempt lifecycle to fail or replan.\n\n## Success vs Failure Decision\n\nReducer task:\n- Treat `<dependencies>` outcomes as context inputs for your `<assigned_task>`.\n- Work on the assigned reducer task, then choose exactly one terminal tool.\n\nCall `submit_reducer_outcome` with `status=\"success\"` when:\n- You finished the assigned reducer work.\n- Your `outcome` summarizes what you completed and the reducer outcome/context\n  that should be carried forward.\n\nCall `submit_reducer_outcome` with `status=\"failed\"` when:\n- You cannot finish the assigned reducer work from the current context.\n- The dependency outcomes are missing, contradictory, insufficient, or expose a\n  blocker that requires another attempt or planner iteration.\n\nDo not submit success just because dependency outcomes look reasonable. Success\nmeans the assigned reducer work is finished; otherwise, submit failure with the\nspecific blocker or missing context.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "definitions": {
        "SubmissionStatus": {
          "description": "`Literal[\"success\", \"failed\"]`.",
          "enum": [
            "success",
            "failed"
          ],
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "properties": {
        "outcome": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "status": {
          "$ref": "#/definitions/SubmissionStatus"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "outcome",
        "status"
      ],
      "title": "OutcomeInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "submit_advisor_feedback",
    "description": "Terminate the advisor with your verdict + summary.\n\nCall this exactly once when:\n- You've reviewed the caller's pending terminal submission against\n  their contract and transcript.\n\nInputs:\n- `verdict`: \"approve\" or \"reject\".\n- `summary`: focused prose covering, in order:\n  1. Tool selection — \"correct\" or \"should be <other_tool>\" with a\n     one-sentence rationale.\n  2. Quality of the work backing the payload — what's solid, what's\n     unsupported. Quote transcript lines or contract fragments.\n  3. Residual risks (or \"None\") — what the caller should weigh on\n     approve, or the single most important fix on reject.\n\nBehavior:\n- The verdict + summary is returned to the caller via `ask_advisor`.\n  The caller decides whether to proceed with their submission or\n  revise.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "definitions": {
        "Verdict": {
          "description": "`Literal[\"approve\", \"reject\"]`.",
          "enum": [
            "approve",
            "reject"
          ],
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "properties": {
        "summary": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "verdict": {
          "$ref": "#/definitions/Verdict"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "summary",
        "verdict"
      ],
      "title": "SubmitAdvisorFeedbackInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "submit_exploration_result",
    "description": "Terminate as an explorer subagent with your read-only findings.\n\nCall this when:\n- You've completed the investigation you were spawned to do.\n- You can present your findings with verifiable references (paths,\n  line numbers, command outputs).\n\nInputs:\n- `summary`: 1–3 sentence recap answering your original question\n  directly.\n- `findings`: bullet list of concrete observations.\n- `references`: list of citable evidence (e.g.,\n  `path/to/file.py:42`, `git log` excerpts) that backs each finding.\n\nBehavior:\n- Your summary is returned to the caller via `run_subagent`'s result.\n\nStyle:\n- You are read-only. Do not propose changes; describe what is.\n- Cite evidence. A finding without a reference is just an assertion.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "findings": {
          "default": [],
          "items": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "type": "array"
        },
        "references": {
          "default": [],
          "items": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "type": "array"
        },
        "summary": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "summary"
      ],
      "title": "SubmitExplorationResultInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "ask_advisor",
    "description": "Ask the advisor for a blocking, read-only audit of the terminal submission\nyou're about to make.\n\nUse this when:\n- You're about to call a terminal tool (e.g., `submit_generator_outcome`,\n  `submit_reducer_outcome`, `submit_planner_outcome`) and you want a\n  second pair of eyes on (1) tool selection and (2) whether the work you've\n  done actually supports the payload.\n- The submission is high-stakes (closes a goal, marks an attempt\n  complete).\n\nDo NOT use for:\n- Trivial submissions where the right terminal is unambiguous and the\n  work is obvious (e.g., a short summary acknowledging an already-passed\n  eval).\n- Fixing problems — the advisor only audits and cannot edit. Reducer\n  agents may apply trivial inline fixes themselves via\n  `edit_file`/`write_file` (typo, wrong variable name, single-line\n  obvious bug); the advisor's job is to confirm those fixes do not exceed\n  that scope before approving a success terminal.\n\nCapabilities and constraints:\n- Read-only. The advisor cannot mutate files.\n- NOT callable inside an isolated workspace. Because every terminal\n  requires a prior advisor approval, terminal submission is impossible\n  while isolated — call `exit_isolated_workspace` first, then\n  `ask_advisor` and submit your terminal.\n- The advisor sees your original task and contract, a filtered version\n  of your transcript, the terminal-tool catalog (with each terminal's\n  review focus), and the submission you're about to make.\n- Lenient approve bar: the advisor approves when your tool choice is\n  right and your payload is plausibly supported, even if the work isn't\n  pristine. It rejects only on real quality problems (wrong terminal,\n  stubs, TODOs, unsupported claims).\n- You get back `approve` / `reject` plus a summary covering: tool\n  selection, payload-vs-work support, residual risks.\n\nInput shape:\n- `tool_name`: the terminal you intend to call.\n- `tool_payload`: the exact arguments you'd pass.\n\nOutput shape:\n- The advisor's summary text, with verdict in metadata.\n\nCommon pitfalls:\n- Calling `ask_advisor` AFTER submitting the terminal — too late. Call\n  BEFORE.\n- Ignoring a prior `reject` and re-asking with the same payload — a\n  caller that ignores prior feedback warrants a sharper second reject.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "tool_name": {
          "description": "The terminal tool the caller intends to call.",
          "type": "string"
        },
        "tool_payload": {
          "additionalProperties": true,
          "default": {},
          "description": "The arguments the caller intends to pass.",
          "type": "object"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "tool_name"
      ],
      "title": "AskAdvisorInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "delegate_workflow",
    "description": "Start non-terminal delegated workflow work. Returns a workflow handle; continue running and use check_workflow_status or cancel_workflow later.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "goal": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "goal"
      ],
      "title": "DelegateWorkflowInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "check_workflow_status",
    "description": "Inspect delegated workflow progress and print terminal outcomes when available.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "workflow_id": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "workflow_task_id": {
          "default": null,
          "type": [
            "string",
            "null"
          ]
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "workflow_id"
      ],
      "title": "CheckWorkflowStatusInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "cancel_workflow",
    "description": "Cancel an outstanding delegated workflow by workflow_task_id.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "reason": {
          "default": "",
          "type": "string"
        },
        "workflow_task_id": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "workflow_task_id"
      ],
      "title": "CancelWorkflowInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "run_subagent",
    "description": "Spawn a registered subagent as a supervised async session. You hand it `prompt` as\nits only input. It must finish by calling its terminal tool; whatever that\nterminal tool emits becomes your result.\n\nUse this when:\n- You need to delegate a focused, context-isolated investigation (e.g.,\n  \"where is X used across the repo?\") so your context isn't polluted by\n  intermediate tool output.\n- You can launch multiple independent investigations and want to run them\n  in parallel — fire them all in a single message with multiple\n  `run_subagent` calls.\n\nDo NOT use for:\n- Work you'd handle in 1–3 of your own tool calls — direct execution\n  beats subagent overhead.\n- Spawning further subagents from inside a subagent — that path is\n  rejected at validation time. Handle the work directly, or submit your\n  findings via your own terminal tool.\n- Tasks that need shared context with you — the subagent does NOT\n  inherit your conversation. The `prompt` is the only channel.\n\nWriting the prompt:\nBrief the subagent like a smart colleague who just walked into the room.\nIt hasn't seen your conversation, doesn't know what you've tried, doesn't\nunderstand why the task matters.\n- Explain what you're trying to accomplish and why.\n- Include the exact paths, symbol names, or commands you'd run yourself.\n- Specify what's in scope and what's out of scope.\n- Tell it what shape of answer you want (\"report in under 200 words\",\n  \"list the file paths\").\n- Terse command-style prompts produce shallow, generic work.\n\nDon't peek. The launch returns a `subagent_session_id`; the subagent\nruns asynchronously. Don't read its transcript or poll progress unless\nthe user explicitly asks for a status check — that defeats the point\nof forking off its tool noise. You'll be notified when it completes.\n\nDon't race. After launching, you know nothing about what the subagent\nwill find. Never predict its result in any format. If the user asks a\nfollow-up before completion, give status, not a guess.\n\nCapabilities and constraints:\n- The launch returns immediately with a `subagent_session_id`.\n- Peek progress with `check_subagent_progress` — you get\n  the last few messages while it's running, the terminal output once it\n  finishes.\n- Cancel with `cancel_subagent`.\n- A subagent that exits without calling a terminal tool is marked\n  failed.\n\nLaunch output:\n- On success: `[SUBAGENT LAUNCHED]` with `subagent_session_id`, `status=running`,\n  and `agent_name`.\n- Metadata includes `subagent_session_id`, `status`, and `agent_name`.\n- Completion is delivered later by typed notification or\n  `check_subagent_progress`; terminal metadata such as\n  `subagent_terminal_called` belongs to that completion result, not the launch.\n\nExample:\n  run_subagent(\n    agent_name=\"explorer\",\n    prompt=(\n      \"Find every call site of \"\n      \"`AttemptOrchestrator.apply_reducer_submission` in backend/src \"\n      \"and report (file, line, calling function). The signature is \"\n      \"changing in PR #842; I need the punch list of files to update. \"\n      \"Report under 200 words.\"\n    ),\n  )\n",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "agent_name": {
          "description": "Name of a registered dispatchable subagent (caller-scoped enum, §6.6).",
          "enum": [
            "explorer",
            "coder"
          ],
          "type": "string"
        },
        "prompt": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "agent_name",
        "prompt"
      ],
      "title": "RunSubagentInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "check_subagent_progress",
    "description": "Check a running or finished subagent by subagent_session_id. Returns the latest child-agent message snapshot while running and the terminal result after successful completion.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "last_n_messages": {
          "default": 5,
          "format": "uint8",
          "maximum": 10.0,
          "minimum": 1.0,
          "type": "integer"
        },
        "subagent_session_id": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "subagent_session_id"
      ],
      "title": "CheckSubagentProgressInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "cancel_subagent",
    "description": "Cancel a running subagent by subagent_session_id.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "reason": {
          "default": "",
          "type": "string"
        },
        "subagent_session_id": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "subagent_session_id"
      ],
      "title": "CancelSubagentInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  },
  {
    "name": "load_skill_reference",
    "description": "Load one named reference document attached to a skill (e.g. a checklist, template, or rubric). Cheaper than loading the full skill. Use after you've read the skill's main instructions and need a specific referenced document. The reference name comes from the skill's index.",
    "input_schema": {
      "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
      "properties": {
        "reference_name": {
          "description": "Exact reference document name to load.",
          "type": "string"
        },
        "skill_name": {
          "description": "Name of the skill that owns the reference.",
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "reference_name",
        "skill_name"
      ],
      "title": "LoadSkillReferenceInput",
      "type": "object"
    },
    "output_schema": null
  }
]
